This case study utilizes these 3 methods to analyze students study habits:

  • ANOVA
  • chi-square tests
  • time series analysis

Data Analysis

Part 1: ANOVA

My hypotheses for this One-way ANOVA is this:

\(H_0: \mu_1{BAPG} = \mu_2{CAGC} = \mu_3{HAGC}\)

\(H_A:\) At least one mean is different

To check whether I reject the Null Hypothesis or not. I will pick 50 random days from each program and conduct the ANOVA analysis

Number of total rows usd for this ANOVA analysis:

## [1] 150

150 means that I got 50 rows from each program, therefore I can proceed to the analysis.

Using the aov() command, I can do the ANOVA calculation and get a summary table:

##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## Program       2   93.4   46.72   7.269 0.000976 ***
## Residuals   147  944.8    6.43                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Interpretation p = 0.00863 < 0.05 = alpha Decision: Reject the null Interpretation: There is statistical difference in the mean of hours. There is statistically significant evidence at the 0.05 level that the mean number of hours studied differs among at least some of the BAPG, CAGC, and HAGC programs.

After conducting the one-way anova to tell us that one of the programs has a different mean of studied hours, I can use the Tukeys HSD method to analyze if there is one program from the 3 programs that has the a different mean.

##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = Study ~ Program, data = programs.combined)
## 
## $Program
##              diff       lwr        upr     p adj
## CAGC-BAPG -0.2422 -1.442731  0.9583313 0.8819444
## HAGC-BAPG -1.7822 -2.982731 -0.5816687 0.0016864
## HAGC-CAGC -1.5400 -2.740531 -0.3394687 0.0079108

p val:

0.54 > 0.05

0.49 > 0.05

0.99 > 0.05 Decision: We reject the null hypothesis that the mean of studied hours is the same across all programs.

In other words, it means there is no statistical significant difference in mean study hours among the programs BAPG, CAGC, and HAGC.

Although the plot suggests that CAGC has the lowest mean hours descriptively, this difference is not statistically significant according to the Tukey HSD test.

Part 2: Chi-Square Tests

3.13 hours is the amount of time spent studying per day by students and McGill University and is purportedly the most in Canada. Using this amount as a baseline, I will select 50 days from each program (150 total) and separate them between Above or Below 3.13 hours. This method will analyze whether the distribution of Above and Below days are the same across all programs.

In order to do a Chi Square test we need to verify the following conditions: 1. Counted Data Condition: Count the study hours from each program by separating them into Below and Above days.

  1. Independence Assumption: Counts should be independent since randomly allocated. Meaning that the 150 days were randomly selected

  2. Randomization Condition: Randomization in packaging that randomly selected the days for this model

  3. Expected Cell Frequency/Sample Size Condition: Calculate in R

Based on the four conditions we can use the Chi Square test for Homogeneity Independence to check whether the study pattern differs for each program.

##        
##         BAPG CAGC HAGC
##   Above   28   33   16
##   Below   22   17   34

\(H_0:\) The distribution of Above vs Below days is the same for all programs (study-hour category is not related to program)

\(H_A:\) The distribution of Above vs Below days is not the same for all programs (study-hour category is related to program)

##        
##             BAPG     CAGC     HAGC
##   Above 25.66667 25.66667 25.66667
##   Below 24.33333 24.33333 24.33333
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  observed.hours
## X-squared = 12.222, df = 2, p-value = 0.002218

Conclusion: Since 0.26 > 0.05, fail to reject the null hypothesis

The data does not provide any evidence to support that the proportions of days for Below vs Average is tied to the program. The observed counts are consistent with hours being independent of program.

##        
##               BAPG       CAGC       HAGC
##   Above  0.4605662  1.4474937 -1.9080599
##   Below -0.4730162 -1.4866222  1.9596384

Mosaic Insights:

BAPG: More than expected student study Above the 3.13 hours, meaning the Below column height is higher than expected CAGC: The Above column height is way smaller than expected, that means more than expected amount of students study less than 3.13 hours HAGC: Both sides Above and Below are on similar height. However, by a small margin the Above column is higher, meaning there are more students studying more than 3.13 hours/day

Forecasting the next 5 days

In order to predict the study hours of the next 5 days, from Dec 6 to 10. I need to use one of the 3 exponential smoothing models. The deciding factor is whether my data has seasonality and trends.

Simple Exponential Smoothing:No seasonality and no trend

Holt (Double) Exponential Smoothing:Has a trend but no seasonality

HoltWinters (Triple) Exponential Smoothing:Has a trend and a seasonality

For my study data I will be using the Holt (Double) Exponential Smoothing, because from previous visualizations it does not have a seasonality, but it has a trend going upwards. Using the Holt (Double) Exponential Smoothing we can forecast what the results will be in the next 5 days.

The outcome is that it will predict I will study another 8 hours for the next 5 days, with the gray bands being th uncertainities.

Final Thoughts and Conclusions:

  1. The study hours average between all student from different programs is different. However the p-value that I calculated using the One-Way Anova was 0.00863<0.05. So we reject the null hypothesis that all programs have the same mean of study hours.

  2. When comparing the mean studies hours from Cambrian students to the McGill study mean, the chisquare test on the Above/Below3.13 by Program table gives p = 0.3511 > 0.05, so the null hypothesis that the distribution of days above vs below 3.13 hours is the same for all programs is not rejected.

The Tukeys HSD mosaic visualizes the difference in mean study hours per program.

The overall takeaway from this analysis is that BAPG and HACGC students study more than McGills students.

  1. The Time Series Analysis shows that my study hours range is anywhere from 1 to 8 (during end of semester it can peak up to 10 hours).

  2. Overall takeaway from my analyzing my study habits is that my data is inconsistent, there are low study days mixed with high study days and vice-versa. This inconsistency can be due to my school, part-time or my hobbies. The most valuable insight from this analysis, is that during the end of semester the average 8 hours of study per day is required, meaning that planning for this period is crucial to make sure I have at least 8 hours of my day to dedicate to my studies.
